    \"symbol\": \"LocalWake\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"chain\": [\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/alloc/src/task.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"raw_waker\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"repo\": \"rust-lang/rust\",\n      \"path\": \"library/alloc/src/task.rs\",\n      \"symbol\": \"local_raw_waker\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"text\": \"The Rust async runtime waker mechanism is implemented across multiple files in the rust-lang/rust standard library. The core waker mechanism is found in `library/core/src/task/wake.rs`, which contains the `RawWaker` struct (a data pointer paired with a static vtable) and `RawWakerVTable` struct (which contains function pointers for cloning, waking, waking-by-ref, and dropping). The `Waker` struct wraps a `RawWaker` and is thread-safe (Send+Sync), while `LocalWaker` is a non-thread-safe variant. The `Context` struct holds a reference to a `Waker` (and optionally a `LocalWaker`) and is passed to future polling.\\n\\nThe polling mechanism is split between several files: `library/core/src/task/poll.rs` defines the `Poll` enum (Ready/Pending), and `library/core/src/future/future.rs` defines the `Future` trait with the core `poll(self: Pin<&mut Self>, cx: &mut Context<'_>) -> Poll<Self::Output>` method. The future polling loop is executed by runtime executors that repeatedly call `Future::poll()` with a `Context` containing a `Waker` - this is exemplified in the documentation examples in `library/alloc/src/task.rs` in the `block_on` function.\\n\\nA safe interface for creating wakers is provided in `library/alloc/src/task.rs` through the `Wake` trait (for thread-safe Arc-based wakers) and `LocalWake` trait (for Rc-based thread-local wakers). These traits use helper functions `raw_waker()` and `local_raw_waker()` to construct `RawWaker` instances with appropriate vtables that manage reference counting and delegate wake calls to the trait implementations.\\n\\nThe helper macro `ready!` in `library/core/src/task/ready.rs` provides syntactic sugar for handling Poll::Pending in polling code, allowing early returns from polling functions.\"\n}\n",
